**Update**

Try [non-correlated][1] sub query from 3.6 for your use case.

Something like 

    Listing.aggregate(
     [{$lookup:{
       from: &quot;ListingLikes&quot;,
       pipeline:[
        {&quot;$match&quot;:{&quot;userId&quot;:{&quot;$eq&quot;:user}}},
        {$project: {_id:0,listingId:1}}
       ],
       as: &quot;noncr&quot;
     }},
     {$match:{
       $expr:{
         $not:[
          {$in:[
            $_id,
            {$arrayElemAt:[&quot;$noncr.listingId&quot;,0]}
          ]}
        ]
      }
    }},
    {$project:{noncr:0}},
    {&quot;$limit&quot;:10}]
    )

[`$lookup`][2] to pull in the &quot;listingId&quot; for user id followed by [`$match`][3] to filter the documents where &quot;_id&quot; is not in list of listingIds.

[`$expr`][4] allows use of aggregation comparison operators in $match stage.

[`$arrayElemAt`][5] to fetch the first element from $lookup array.

[`$in`][6] to compare the _id against listingIds. 

[`$project`][7] with exclusion to remove the &quot;noncr&quot; field from the final response.

Please note when you test query  use the collection name not model or schema name in &quot;from&quot; attribute of look up stage.


  [1]: https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/operator/aggregation/lookup/#uncorrelated-subquery
  [2]: https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/operator/aggregation/lookup/index.html
  [3]: https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/operator/aggregation/match/index.html
  [4]: https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/operator/query/expr/index.html
  [5]: https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/operator/aggregation/arrayElemAt/index.html
  [6]: https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/operator/aggregation/in/index.html
  [7]: https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/operator/aggregation/project/index.html

