The problem with this code seems like your input is not `Integer` based. `s.hasNext()` checks for input that could be cast to `String`. You probably should use `s.hasNextInt()` here. Or you could change the `s.nextInt()` to `s.next()` it will take input as a `String`. I am providing two possible solutions, then you can decide which one fulfills your requirements.

**Solution 1:** 

    ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt; list = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    while (s.hasNextInt()) {
        list.add(s.nextInt());
    }

In this solution, your code will only take `Integer` as input. Because `s.hasNextInt()` restricts the input to `Integer` value. If it encounters anything other than the `Integer` value then the `while` loop will exit.

**Solution 2:** 

    ArrayList&lt;String&gt; list = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    while (s.hasNext()) {
        list.add(s.next());
    }

In this solution, your code will take `String` as input. It won&#39;t fail whether your input contains `&quot;abc&quot;` or `7` or `33.32` etc. It will save all of them as a `String` value.

